SIMPLE: third
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Third
<hw>Third</hw> <pr>(th⟦etil⟧rd)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>thirde</ets>, AS. <ets>⟦thorn⟧ridda</ets>, fr.
<ets>⟦thorn⟧r⟦imac⟧</ets>, <ets>⟦thorn⟧re⟦oacute⟧</ets>, three; akin to
D. <ets>derde</ets> third, G. <ets>dritte</ets>, Icel.
<ets>⟦thorn⟧ri⟦edh⟧i</ets>, Goth. <ets>⟦thorn⟧ridja</ets>, L.
<ets>tertius</ets>, Gr. <grk>tri`tos</grk>, Skr.
<ets>t⟦rsdot⟧t⟦imac⟧ya</ets>. See <er>Three</er>, and cf.
<er>Riding</er> a jurisdiction, <er>Tierce</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Next after the second; coming after two others; -- the ordinal of
three; <as>as, the <ex>third</ex> hour in the day</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The
<xex>third</xex> night.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Constituting or being one of three equal parts into
which anything is divided; <as>as, the <ex>third</ex> part of a
day</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Third estate</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>In England, the
commons, or the commonalty, who are represented in Parliament by the
House of Commons.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>In France, the tiers
⟦eacute⟧tat.</cd> See <er>Tiers ⟦eacute⟧tat</er>. <col><b>Third
order</b></col> <fld>(R. C. Ch.)</fld>, <cd>an order attached to a
monastic order, and comprising men and women devoted to a rule of pious
living, called the third rule, by a simple vow if they remain seculars,
and by more solemn vows if they become regulars. See <er>Tertiary</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>, 1.</cd> -- <col><b>Third person</b></col>
<fld>(Gram.)</fld>, <cd>the person spoken of. See <er>Person</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>, 7.</cd> -- <col><b>Third sound</b></col>.
<fld>(Mus.)</fld> <cd>See <er>Third</er>, <pos>n.</pos>,
3.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Third</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Third
<hw>Third</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The quotient
of a unit divided by three; one of three equal parts into which anything
is divided.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The sixtieth part of a second of time.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>The third tone of the scale; the
mediant.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>The third part of
the estate of a deceased husband, which, by some local laws, the widow
is entitled to enjoy during her life.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Major third</b></col> <fld>(Mus.)</fld>, <cd>an interval
of two tones.</cd> -- <col><b>Minor third</b></col> <fld>(Mus.)</fld>,
<cd>an interval of a tone and a half.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Third-borough</ent>⟦br⟧
